<chapter xml:id="chapter-symb-lang" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Symbolic language</title>


<section xml:id="section-symb-lang-statements">
<title>Statements</title>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>statement</title>
	<idx>statement(s) (in logic)</idx>
	<idx><h>logical</h><h>statement(s)</h></idx>
	<p>a sentence that is either true or false</p>
</li></dl></p>

<example xml:id="example-symb-lang-basic-statements">
	<title>Logical statements</title>
	<p><ol>
		<li xml:id="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-simple">
		<!-- old label EXAMPLE::basic.simple.statement.eg -->
			All prime numbers are odd.
		</li>
		<li xml:id="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-compound">
		<!-- old label EXAMPLE::basic.compound.statement.eg -->
			Some trees have leaves and some trees have needles.
		</li>
		<li xml:id="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-conditional">
		<!-- old label EXAMPLE::basic.conditional.statement.eg -->
			If you pay attention in class and work through all the homework problems,
			then you will do well in this course.
		</li>
	</ol>
</p></example>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>substatement</title>
	<idx><h>statement (in logic)</h><h>sub-</h></idx>
	<idx><h>logical</h><h>substatement</h></idx>
	<idx>substatement</idx>
	<p>	part of a logical statement that could be considered a statement on its own </p>
</li></dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Substatements</title>
	<p>
	<q>Some trees have leaves</q> is a substatement of
	<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-compound">statement</xref>
	in
	<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements" />.
</p></example>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>simple statement</title>
		<idx><h>simple</h><h>statement</h></idx>
		<idx><h>statement (in logic)</h><h>simple</h></idx>
		<p>	does not contain any proper substatements </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>compound statement</title>
		<idx><h>compound</h><h>statement</h></idx> <!-- TODO will there be any other compound entries in the index? -->
		<idx><h>statement (in logic)</h><h>compound</h></idx>
		<p>	contains two or more substatements </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>connective</title>
		<idx>connective(s)</idx>
		<idx><h>statement (in logic)</h><h>connective</h></idx>
		<p>	a connecting word between substatements in a compound statement </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Simple and compound statements</title>
	<p>
	Reconsidering the statements in <xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements" />:
	<ol>
		<li>
			<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-simple">statement</xref>
			is simple;
		</li>
		<li>
			<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-compound">statement</xref>
			is a compound statement made up of two (simple) substatements linked by the connective <q>and</q>;
			and
		</li>
		<li>
			<xref ref="example-symb-lang-basic-statements-conditional">statement</xref>
			is a compound statement made up of two substatements linked by the connective <q>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /></q>,
			where the substatement that constitutes the <q>if</q> part is itself a compound statement.
		</li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</example>

<p> The substatements in a compound statement can be related to each other by <term>connectives</term> in various ways.</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-symb-lang-connectives">
	<title>Five basic connectives</title>
	<idx>connective(s)</idx>
	<idx><h>logical</h><h>connectives</h></idx>
	<statement>
		<p><dl width="narrow">
			<li>
				<title>negation</title>
				<idx>negation</idx>
				<idx>not (logical connective)</idx>
				<idx><h>logical</h><h>negation</h></idx>
				<p> <q>not</q> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>conjuction</title>
				<idx>conjuction</idx>
				<idx>and (logical connective)</idx>
				<idx><h>logical</h><h>conjuction</h></idx>
				<p> <q>and</q> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>disjunction</title>
				<idx>disjunction</idx>
				<idx>or (logical connective)</idx>
				<idx><h>logical</h><h>disjunction</h></idx>
				<p> <q>or</q> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>conditional</title>
				<idx>conditional</idx>
				<idx>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /> (logical connective)</idx>
				<idx><h>logical</h><h>conditional</h></idx>
				<p> <q>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /></q> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>biconditional</title>
				<idx>biconditional</idx>
				<idx>if and only if (logical connective)</idx>
				<idx><h>logical</h><h>biconditional</h></idx>
				<p> <q>if and only if</q> </p>
			</li>
		</dl></p>
		<p>
		Given statements <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
		we use these connectives to construct new statements:
		<dl width="narrow">
			<li>
				<title>negation of <m>A</m></title>
				<p> not <m>A</m> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>conjuction of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
				<p> <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>disjunction of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
				<p> <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>conditional where <m>A</m> implies <m>B</m></title>
				<p> if <m>A</m> then <m>B</m> </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<title>biconditional involving <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
				<p> <m>A</m> if and only if <m>B</m> </p>
			</li>
		</dl>
		</p>
	</statement>
</definition>

<remark xml:id="remark-symb-lang-connectives"><p><ol>
	<li>
		All statements we will consider can be constructed starting from a finite number of simple statements and modifying/joining them using connectives as above.
	</li>
	<li xml:id="remark-symb-lang-connectives-inclusive-exclusive-or">
	<!-- old label NOTE::inclusive.exclusive.or -->
		<em>Always</em> take <q><m>A</m> or <m>B</m></q> to mean <q><m>A</m> or <m>B</m> or both</q>
		(known as <term>inclusive or</term><idx>inclusive or</idx>).
		However, in everyday language it may be reasonable to take
		<q><em>either</em> <m>A</m> or <m>B</m></q>
		to mean
		<q>(<m>A</m> or <m>B</m>) and not (<m>A</m> and <m>B</m>)</q>
		(known as <term>exclusive or</term><idx>exclusive or</idx>).
	</li>
	<li>
		The <term>conditional</term> and <term>biconditional</term> connectives are actually superfluous
		<mdash /> they can be constructed from the first three.
		(See
		<xref ref="wexample-logic-equiv-construct-conditional" />
		and <xref ref="exercise-logic-equiv-biconditional-constructed" />.)
		But they occur frequently,
		and such constructions from other connectives obscure their meaning,
		so it is more convenient to include these two connectives in our list of of basic connectives.
	</li>
</ol></p></remark>

<example>
	<title>Translating everyday English into logical statements</title>
	<p>
	A conversation.
	<dl width="narrow">
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> It is raining. </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> No, it isn't. </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> Either it's raining or it isn't. </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> How can we decide? </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> If we go outside and we get wet, then it's raining. </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> We'd get wet outside if the sprinklers are on, too. </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> Don't be silly! </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice (continuing<ellipsis />)</title><p> We'll get wet if it's raining, and this is the only way we'll get wet. </p> </li>
	</dl>
	</p>
	<p>
	Let us rewrite the above conversation to clearly identify the substatements and connectives.
	<dl width="narrow">
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> it is raining </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> not (it is raining) </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> (it is raining) or (not (it is raining)) </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> <em>[not a statement!]</em> </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> if ((we are outside) and (we get wet)) then (it is raining) </p> </li>
		<li><title>Bob</title><p> if ((we are outside) and (the sprinklers are on)) then (we get wet) </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> <em>[not a statement!]</em> </p> </li>
		<li><title>Alice</title><p> if (we are outside) then ((we get wet) if and only if (it is raining)) </p> </li>
	</dl>
	</p>
</example>

<claim> <!-- claim has been hijacked to Test -->
	<title>Checking whether a sentence is a logical statement</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>statement</h></idx>
	<idx><h>statement(s) (in logic)</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>logical</h><h>statement(s)</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<statement><p>
		If <m>S</m> is an English language sentence and the phrase <q>It is true that <m>S</m></q> makes sense as an English language sentence,
		then <m>S</m> is a logical statement.
	</p></statement>
</claim>

<p>
Strictly speaking,
many mathematical statements are not logical statements,
for a different reason then the one used in the test above.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-symb-lang-free-variable-not-a-statement">
	<!-- old label EXAMPLE::free.variable.not.a.statement -->
	<title>An ambiguous mathematical statement</title>
	<p>
	The phrase <q><m>f</m> is a differentiable function</q> is not a logical statement,
	since whether it is true or false depends on the <term>free variable</term> <m>f</m>.
	For example,
	if we substitute the function <m>f(x) = x</m> into this statement,
	the statement becomes true.
	However,
	if we substitute the function <m>f(x) = \abs{x}</m>,
	the statement becomes false.
	We will deal with this issue in <xref ref="chapter-pred-logic" />.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-symb-lang-symb-lang">
<title>Converting language to symbols</title>

<p>
As we have already begun to do,
we will use letters to represent (possibly variable) logical statements and substatements.
To complete the conversion from verbose language to compact symbolism,
we will introduce symbols to represent the <term><xref ref="definition-symb-lang-connectives" text="title" /></term>.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>negation of <m>A</m></title>
		<idx><h>negation</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>not (logical connective)</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>negation</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\lgcnot A</m></usage>
			<description>logical negation of statement <m>A</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>\lgcnot A</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>conjuction of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
		<idx><h>conjuction</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>and (logical connective)</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>conjuction</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>A \lgcand B</m></usage>
			<description>logical conjunction of statements <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>A \lgcand B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>disjunction of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
		<idx><h>disjunction</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>or (logical connective)</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>disjunction</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>A \lgcor B</m></usage>
			<description>logical disjunction of statements <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>A \lgcor B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>conditional where <m>A</m> implies <m>B</m></title>
		<idx><h>conditional</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /> (logical connective)</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>conditional</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>A \lgccond B</m></usage>
			<description>logical conditional where statement <m>A</m> implies statement <m>B</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>A \lgccond B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>biconditional involving <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></title>
		<idx><h>biconditional</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>if and only if (logical connective)</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>biconditional</h><h>notation for</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>A \lgcbicond B</m></usage>
			<description>
				logical biconditional where each of statements <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> implies the other
			</description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>A \lgcbicond B</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<p>
Using variables to represent statements and the above symbols to represent connectives allows us to isolate the task of analyzing logical structure,
without being distracted or influenced by the content of the statements.
</p>

<warning><p>
	In mathematics, the symbol <m>\to</m> is also used in function notation;
	<!-- (see TODO-XREF); \S\zref{CHAPTER::funcs} -->
	you will need to determine from the context which role this symbol is playing.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title>Translating English language into symbolic language</title>
	<p>
	Consider the statement <q>if we are outside and we get wet then it is raining.</q>
	Assign statement variables:
	<!-- TODO these are actual unicode quote symbols in there, works OK for HTML but what about latex ? -->
	<md><mrow>
		A \amp = \text{ “we are outside,”} \amp
		B \amp = \text{ “we get wet,”} \amp
		C \amp = \text{ “it is raining.”}
	</mrow></md>
	Then symbolically, the statement can be written <md>A \lgcand B \lgccond C</md>.
	</p>
</example>

<remark><p>
	Using <em>substatement</em> variables is not the same as using <em>free</em> variables.
	You should think of substatement variables as placeholders for specific logical statements which,
	by definition,
	can each be determined to be either true or false.
</p></remark>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-symb-lang-logic-analysis">
<title>Logical analysis</title>

<p>
We will now leave the English language behind and concentrate on logical statements consisting only of variables and connectives.
Keep in mind that variables are not limited to representing simple statements;
they can represent compound statements as well.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>truth value</title>
		<idx><h>truth</h><h>value</h></idx>
		<p> the property of being true or false </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<p>
Given a logical statement,
view the variables as <em>inputs</em> and the truth value of the entire statement as an <em>output</em>.
We would like a systematic way to determine how the truth value of the output changes as we vary the truth values of the inputs.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>logical analysis</title>
		<idx><h>logical</h><h>analysis</h></idx>
		<p> the process of determining the truth value of a statement based on the truth values of its variable substatements </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>truth table</title>
		<idx><h>truth</h><h>table</h></idx>
		<p> tabular method of carrying out logical analysis </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<p>
If a statement involves a finite number of variables,
then since each variable can have one of only two possible truth values,
there are a finite number of different combinations of input truth values for the statement.
So we can test each combination one after the other to determine all possible outputs.
Arrange this analysis in a table with all possibilities for the input variables on the left and the resulting outputs on the right.
</p>

<note xml:id="note-symb-lang-num-rows-truth-table"><p>
<!-- \label{NOTE::num.rows.truth.table} -->
	In fact,
	if there are <m>n</m> variables,
	then there are exactly <m>2^n</m> different combinations of truth values for the variables.
	<!--
	(see TODO-XREF).
		Exercise \ref{EXERCISE::counting::num.truth.tables} of \S\zref{CHAPTER::counting}
		BUT there are also activities using induction for this ... ?
	-->
</p></note>

<p>
First, let's establish the truth tables of the basic connectives
(that is, of statements containing exactly one connective).
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-symb-lang-connectives-truth-tables">
<!-- \label{TABLE::basic.connectives} -->
	<caption>The truth tables of the <term><xref ref="definition-symb-lang-connectives" text="title" /></term>.</caption>
	<idx><h>connective(s)</h><h>truth tables for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>statement (in logic)</h><h>connective</h><h>truth tables for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>truth</h><h>table</h><h>for each of the connectives</h></idx>
	<idx><h>negation</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>not (logical connective)</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>conjuction</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>and (logical connective)</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>disjunction</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>or (logical connective)</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>conditional</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>if <ellipsis /> then <ellipsis /> (logical connective)</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>biconditional</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>if and only if (logical connective)</h><h>truth table for</h></idx>

	<sidebyside valign="middle">

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell colspan="2" halign="center"><term>Negation</term></cell>
			</row>
			<row><cell colspan="2" /></row>
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcnot p</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell colspan="3" halign="center"><term>Conjunction</term></cell>
			</row>
			<row><cell colspan="3" /></row>
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p</m></cell>
				<cell><m>q</m></cell>
				<cell><m>p \lgcand q</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell colspan="3" halign="center"><term>Disjunction</term></cell>
			</row>
			<row><cell colspan="3" /></row>
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p</m></cell>
				<cell><m>q</m></cell>
				<cell><m>p \lgcor q</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell colspan="3" halign="center"><term>Conditional</term></cell>
			</row>
			<row><cell colspan="3" /></row>
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p</m></cell>
				<cell><m>q</m></cell>
				<cell><m>p \lgccond q</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="medium">
				<cell colspan="3" halign="center"><term>Biconditional</term></cell>
			</row>
			<row><cell colspan="3" /></row>
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p</m></cell>
				<cell><m>q</m></cell>
				<cell><m>p \lgcbicond q</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<note><p><ol>
	<li> Conjunction <m>p \lgcand q</m> is true <em>only</em> when <em>both</em> <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are true. </li>
	<li>
		<p> Disjunction <m>p \lgcor q</m> is true when <em>at least one</em> of <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> is true. </p>
		<!-- <aside><title>See</title><p>
			<xref ref="remark-symb-lang-connectives-inclusive-exclusive-or" text="type-local">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="remark-symb-lang-connectives" />
			regarding inclusive versus exclusive or.
		</p></aside> -->
		<aside><title>See</title><p>
			<xref ref="remark-symb-lang-connectives-inclusive-exclusive-or">Statement</xref>
			of <xref ref="remark-symb-lang-connectives" /> for the difference between <term>inclusive or</term> and <term>exclusive or</term>.
		</p></aside>
	</li>
	<li>
		The first two rows of the truth table for <m>p \lgccond q</m> are consistent with the reading <q>if <m>p</m> is true then <m>q</m> is also true.</q>
		Really, this reading of the conditional says <em>nothing</em> in the case that <m>p</m> is actually false,
		but we cannot leave the <q>output</q> column of the truth table blank for the corresponding rows where <m>p = \lgcfalse</m>.
		Instead, the outputs in the last two rows of the truth table for <m>p \lgccond q</m> are <q>default</q> values chosen to avoid inconsistencies.
		(See <xref ref="exercise-symb-lang-choices-for-implies" />.)
	</li>
	<li>
		Looking at all four rows of the truth table for <m>p \lgccond q</m>,
		we can succinctly say that <m>p \lgccond q</m> is true <em>except</em> when <m>p</m> is true but <m>q</m> is false.
	</li>
	<li>
		Biconditional <m>p \lgcbicond q</m> reads <q><m>p</m> is true when <m>q</m> is true, and <em>only</em> when <m>q</m> is true.</q>
		But this means that when <m>q</m> is false,
		<m>p</m> cannot be true, hence must by false,
		which explains the fourth row of the truth table.
	</li>
	<li>
		Looking at all four rows of the truth table for <m>p \lgcbicond q</m>,
		we can succinctly say that <m>p \lgcbicond q</m> is true when <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> have the <em>same truth value</em>.
	</li>
</ol></p></note>

<p>
We can now use the truth tables of the basic connectives to analyze more complicated statements.
Liberal use of extra <q>intermediate</q> columns to analyze substatements separately is highly recommended.
</p>

<problem xml:id="wexample-symb-lang-neg-bicond"> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p> Analyze <m>\lgcnot (p \lgcbicond q)</m>. </p></statement>
	<solution><tabular halign="center">
		<col /><col right="minor" /><col right="minor" /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
			<cell><m>p</m></cell>
			<cell><m>q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>p \lgcbicond q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcnot (p \lgcbicond q)</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular></solution>
</problem>

<note><p>
	The logical statement <m>\lgcnot (p \lgcbicond q)</m> analyzed in <xref ref="wexample-symb-lang-neg-bicond" /> is one way to realize <em>exclusive or</em>:
	<m>p</m> or <m>q</m> but not both.
</p></note>

<problem>
	<statement><p> Analyze <m>(p \lgcand q) \lgccond (p \lgcbicond r)</m>. </p></statement>
	<solution><tabular halign="center">
		<col /><col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col right="minor" /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
			<cell><m>p</m></cell>
			<cell><m>q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>r</m></cell>
			<cell><m>p \lgcand q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>p \lgcbicond r</m></cell>
			<cell><m>(p \lgcand q) \lgccond (p \lgcbicond r)</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular></solution>
</problem>

<problem>
	<statement><p> Analyze <m>\bbrac{(p\lgccond q) \lgccond r} \lgcbicond \bbrac{p \lgccond (q \lgccond r)}</m>. </p></statement>
	<solution><tabular halign="center">
		<col /><col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col right="minor" /><col /><col right="minor" /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
			<cell><m>p</m></cell>
			<cell><m>q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>r</m></cell>
			<cell><m>p \lgccond q</m></cell>
			<cell><m>q \lgccond r</m></cell>
			<cell><m>A</m></cell>
			<cell><m>B</m></cell>
			<cell><m>A \lgcbicond B</m></cell>
		</row><row>
			<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
